flowRoot.flowPara: If there aren't any per-display settings to expose for the other display, a simple heading is shown instead of the display selector drop down.
Problems with the previous iteration of these designs
When joined, there were two representations of each display (one in the panel and one in the display dialog). More elegant to have a single one for rotation and placement.
Multiple representations of each display in the panel - one in the preview box and another in the display list - again, not very elegant.
Isolating the settings for each display doesn't make sense when mirroring - when things like resolution are shared.
Display switch shouldn't allow all displays to be turned off at once - one should flip on when the final one is turned off.
Redesign goals

Displays are generally configured as a whole: you either use them to mirror,or as an extended workspace, or to present. Make these modes the high-level way in which displays are configured, in order to more closely reflect user intent.
Reduce the amount of work and UI complexity by bringing controls forward and integrating them, rather than using per-display options in settings dialogs.
Presentation mode: displays aren't joined and the presentation display is used for content display (presentation slides, photo slideshows, etc).
FIXME: need to communicate when graphics hardware resources have been exceeded.
FIXME: solution for giving ad hoc demos. Possibly a special workspace that is mirrored. Need to communicate this from the panel.
Not showing numbers to identify displays here, since it wouldn't look very professional in a presentatation scenario. This could be revisited though.
It isn't possible to show unique numbers to identify each display when mirroring, so don't show them in this mode.
